# ACS / OpenClaw Memory Policy

## Purpose

This policy defines how Dreaming Mode classifies memory and prevents uncontrolled memory growth.

Dreaming outputs are proposals. Canonical memory requires Core review or an explicitly approved workflow.

## Memory Classes

| Class | Definition | Storage Recommendation | Retention / Expiration | Promotion Criteria | Owner |
| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |
| Ephemeral | Temporary execution detail with little future value | Local run notes only | Expire after current run or same day | Usually not promoted | Agent |
| Session | Useful for the current work cycle or sprint | Current sprint/status notes | Expire after sprint or when task closes | Can become Nucleus if still relevant | Agent or sprint owner |
| Nucleus | Relevant to one Axodus domain | Nucleus dream or nucleus instructions | Review periodically by nucleus owner | Stable, domain-specific, non-secret | Nucleus owner |
| Cross-Nucleus | Affects multiple Axodus domains | Coordinator digest and memory candidates | Keep until Core review | Impacts multiple nuclei and is stable | ACS Coordinator |
| Canonical Candidate | Proposed stable project truth pending review | Memory candidate registry or Core review report | Keep until accepted/rejected | Stable, sourced, useful, non-secret | Core reviewer |
| Canonical | Approved source-of-truth knowledge | Core registry or approved `.instructions` location | Persistent until superseded | Explicit approval or accepted Core workflow | Core |

## Examples

### Ephemeral

- today's failed command;
- temporary local install problem;
- transient branch issue;
- noisy runtime log with no architectural impact.

### Session

- current sprint objective;
- pending implementation task;
- validation checklist for the active work cycle;
- temporary blocker that should be revisited soon.

### Nucleus

- Governance uses Constitutional and Local governance models;
- Academy distributes Locked/Unlocked `$Neurons`;
- Trading separates backtest, paper, live, and treasury execution.

### Cross-Nucleus

- Core Registry is the canonical source of truth;
- ACS agents must consume Core docs;
- AxodusAPP is a frontend orchestrator for multiple nuclei;
- governance/security rules constrain operational agent behavior.

### Canonical Candidate

- an explicitly confirmed nucleus ownership decision;
- a stable architecture decision repeated across validated sprint reports;
- an accepted terminology rule pending placement in Core docs.

### Canonical

- official Axodus nuclei list;
- governance-first architecture;
- `$Neurons` token naming;
- approved product boundaries;
- architectural decisions already accepted into Core documentation.

## What Agents Should Remember

Agents should propose memory candidates for:

- stable architecture decisions;
- approved terminology;
- nucleus ownership;
- sprint outcomes;
- unresolved blockers;
- cross-nucleus dependencies;
- user or project preferences that affect future planning;
- governance/security rules;
- canonical repository paths;
- decisions explicitly confirmed by the project owner.

## What Agents Must Not Remember

Agents must not persist:

- credentials;
- private keys;
- secrets;
- wallet seed phrases;
- API keys;
- auth headers;
- private tokens;
- temporary logs without impact;
- speculative ideas not approved;
- duplicate summaries;
- emotional noise;
- obsolete implementation details;
- failed experiments unless they became known constraints;
- raw runtime logs containing sensitive payloads.

## Promotion Rules

A memory candidate can be promoted only if it is:

- stable;
- explicitly approved or repeatedly confirmed by reliable sources;
- useful across future sessions;
- non-secret;
- non-temporary;
- non-speculative;
- aligned with Axodus architecture;
- assigned to a clear owner.

## Rejection Rules

Reject or downgrade a candidate when it is:

- too temporary;
- insufficiently sourced;
- duplicated elsewhere;
- speculative;
- sensitive or secret-bearing;
- obsolete;
- relevant only to a local session;
- contradicted by Core or Governance documentation.

## Storage Rules

- Store local agent dreams under `~/.openclaw/main_workspace/dreaming/outputs/agents/<agent-name>/`.
- Store nucleus dreams under `~/.openclaw/main_workspace/dreaming/outputs/nuclei/<nucleus-name>/`.
- Store coordinator digests under `~/.openclaw/main_workspace/dreaming/outputs/coordinator/`.
- Store memory candidates under `~/.openclaw/main_workspace/dreaming/outputs/memory-candidates/`.
- Store review packages under `~/.openclaw/main_workspace/dreaming/outputs/registry-sync/`.

## Security Rule

If a candidate contains or implies sensitive material, redact or block it before persistence. Do not store the raw value in any memory class.
